<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1910-03-30T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1910-03-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="634" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d634">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 23814/11.</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                Ambassador <persName type="to">Reid</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1910-03-30"><hi rend="italic">March 30,
                                1910</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 1261.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The department has received your No. 1216
                            of the 18th instant, in regard to the anticipated emigration to the
                            United States of the British subject Alfred Lumb, a confessed
                            counterfeiter.</p>
                        <p>The department approves your note to the foreign office on the
                            subject.</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer>(For <signed>Mr. Knox</signed>.)<lb/><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>